I recently enjoyed this 1996 Taittinger Comtes de Champagne Rosé. Simply amazing…
/* 
In English-speaking countries, we usually refer to the Champagne house as Tat-in-ger. However, to say it with local French flair you would say Tet-ahn–zhay. 
/* 
Taittinger ages its Comtes de Champagne and Comtes de Champagne Rosé wines in crayères, a 2.5-mile underground network of chalk caves. Originally dug by the Romans, the caves provide the perfect conditions for cellaring wine. Taittinger is one of just five Champagne houses that age their wines in this way. 
/* 
While fans of the James Bond movie franchise might associate the British spy with Bollinger, as I do, but did you know in the original Ian Fleming novels Bond drank Taittinger? In “Casino Royale,” the first in Fleming’s series, Bond describes Taittinger as “probably the finest Champagne in the world.”
